            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ivan Orlov\u2019s story began not in the fog of San Francisco, but in the final, crumbling years of the Soviet Union. Born in Moscow, his early childhood was marked by scarcity and uncertainty, which instilled in him a deep appreciation for stability and opportunity. When his family immigrated to San Francisco in the early 90s, settling in the Russian community of the Richmond District, teenage Ivan felt he had landed on another planet.\n\nHe enrolled in a Business Administration program at San Francisco State University, intending to pursue a conventional path to success. However, the immediate need to support his family and the allure of earning his own money pulled him into the city\u2019s vibrant restaurant scene. He started as a busser, but his quiet authority, sharp eye for detail, and innate grasp of numbers saw him quickly promoted to waiter, then bartender, and eventually shift supervisor. He discovered he learned more about profit-and-loss statements on the back of a napkin during closing than he ever did in a lecture hall. He never finished his degree.\n\nA key turning point came in his late twenties when he was hired as an assistant manager at a sleek new restaurant in Hayes Valley. He thrived under the pressure, mastering inventory, staffing, and the delicate art of managing both entitled patrons and temperamental chefs. Now, at 45, he is the General Manager, earning a respectable income and the trust of the restaurant\u2019s ownership group.\n\nIvan\u2019s life is one of disciplined routine. He lives in a clean, minimalist apartment in Nob Hill, a world away from the busy family home of his youth. His 0.8-mile walk to work is a cherished ritual, a time to clear his head as he descends the hill into the bustling energy of Hayes Valley. His social life is entwined with his profession; his closest friends are a sommelier and a chef from another restaurant. A long-term relationship ended amicably a few years ago, leaving him single but not lonely.\n\nWhile he is proud of his career, Ivan\u2019s ultimate dream is not to manage but to create. He harbors a quiet aspiration to one day open his own small, intimate bistro\u2014perhaps serving elevated Russian classics with a Californian twist. For Ivan, San Francisco is not just a city; it's the place that allowed a boy from Moscow to build a life, and he hopes to one day add his own permanent flavor to its culinary landscape."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight, clutching his mother\u2019s hand in a drab Moscow market. Amidst sacks of potatoes and beets, one vendor had a single, perfect orange. Its impossible brightness was a shock of color in a grey world. He understood instantly it was a treasure they could never afford. That vivid, unattainable fruit became his first real memory of scarcity and desire, planting a quiet determination to one day build a life where such simple beauty was not a miracle, but a choice.\n\n2.\nAt nineteen, he was a busser, overwhelmed by the speed of San Francisco and the cadence of English. One night, a couple left a crisp twenty-dollar bill just for him. He remembers staring at it, the first money that was truly his, earned directly through his own hard work. It was more than cash; it was tangible proof that effort was rewarded here. In that moment, the abstract promise of America became real, and he knew his future was on the restaurant floor, not in a lecture hall.\n\n3.\nHe was thirty-two, the new assistant manager in Hayes Valley. A famous chef and a powerful diner were escalating towards a shouting match when he stepped between them. He doesn't remember what he said, only the feeling of the room\u2019s tension dissolving under his calm, quiet authority. He watched both men defer to him\u2014the outsider, the Russian kid. It was the first time he felt he wasn\u2019t just surviving in San Francisco, but that he truly understood it, and could command his own space within it.\n\n4.\nThe end of his eight-year relationship came not with a fight, but with a shared pot of tea at their kitchen table. He was forty-two. They both acknowledged, with a profound and gentle sadness, that their paths had diverged. The amicable split wasn\u2019t a failure, but a necessary pruning. It taught him the critical difference between being alone and being lonely. This newfound solitude cleared the way for his own ambition, allowing the dream of his bistro to become the central, grounding relationship in his life.\n\n5.\nLast year, on his ritual walk down the hill, he saw a \"For Lease\" sign on a small, promising corner space. He stopped, peering through the grimy window. In that instant, his vague dream of a bistro became intensely specific. He could see the dark wood tables, smell the elevated borscht, and hear the quiet murmur of happy diners. The vision was so powerful, so complete, it felt less like an aspiration and more like a memory from the future, urging him forward."
